---
description: Enforces modern Angular patterns and best practices
globs: src/**/*.component.ts, src/**/*.service.ts, src/**/*.directive.ts, src/**/*.pipe.ts
alwaysApply: true
---

- **Use Signals for Reactive State Management**
  - Prefer signals over BehaviorSubject/Observable for component state
  - Use computed() for derived values
  - Use effect() for side effects
  ```typescript
  // ✅ DO: Use signals
  count = signal(0);
  doubledCount = computed(() => this.count() * 2);
  
  // ❌ DON'T: Use BehaviorSubject
  count$ = new BehaviorSubject(0);
  ```

- **Use Functional Injection Pattern**
  - Prefer inject() function over constructor injection
  - Keeps components leaner, especially with standalone components
  ```typescript
  // ✅ DO: Use functional injection
  export class ExampleComponent {
    private http = inject(HttpClient);
    private service = inject(DataService);
  }
  
  // ❌ DON'T: Use constructor injection
  export class ExampleComponent {
    constructor(
      private http: HttpClient,
      private service: DataService
    ) {}
  }
  ```

- **Implement Lifecycle Interfaces**
  - Always implement the corresponding interface for lifecycle hooks
  - Improves type safety and code readability
  ```typescript
  // ✅ DO: Implement interfaces
  export class ExampleComponent implements OnInit, OnDestroy {
    ngOnInit(): void { /* ... */ }
    ngOnDestroy(): void { /* ... */ }
  }
  
  // ❌ DON'T: Skip interface implementation
  export class ExampleComponent {
    ngOnInit() { /* ... */ }
    ngOnDestroy() { /* ... */ }
  }
  ```

- **Use Standalone Components**
  - Prefer standalone components over NgModule-based components
  - Import dependencies directly in the component
  ```typescript
  // ✅ DO: Use standalone components
  @Component({
    standalone: true,
    imports: [CommonModule, RouterModule],
    // ...
  })
  export class ExampleComponent {}
  
  // ❌ DON'T: Default to NgModule-based components
  @Component({
    // No standalone property
    // ...
  })
  export class ExampleComponent {}
  ```

- **Use OnPush Change Detection**
  - Default to OnPush change detection for better performance
  ```typescript
  // ✅ DO: Use OnPush
  @Component({
    changeDetection: ChangeDetectionStrategy.OnPush,
    // ...
  })
  export class ExampleComponent {}
  ```

- **Use Typed Forms**
  - Always specify types for FormGroup and FormControl
  ```typescript
  // ✅ DO: Use typed forms
  interface UserForm {
    name: FormControl<string>;
    email: FormControl<string>;
  }
  
  userForm = new FormGroup<UserForm>({
    name: new FormControl('', { nonNullable: true }),
    email: new FormControl('', { nonNullable: true })
  });
  
  // ❌ DON'T: Use untyped forms
  userForm = new FormGroup({
    name: new FormControl(''),
    email: new FormControl('')
  });
  ```

- **Avoid Direct DOM Manipulation**
  - Use Angular's abstraction (Renderer2) instead of direct DOM APIs
  ```typescript
  // ✅ DO: Use Renderer2
  constructor(private renderer: Renderer2, private el: ElementRef) {
    this.renderer.addClass(this.el.nativeElement, 'active');
  }
  
  // ❌ DON'T: Manipulate DOM directly
  ngAfterViewInit() {
    this.element.nativeElement.classList.add('active');
  }
  ```

- **Use Host Bindings in Decorator**
  - Prefer host bindings in the component/directive decorator over @HostBinding/@HostListener decorators
  - Keeps all metadata in a single place and improves readability
  ```typescript
  // ✅ DO: Use host in decorator
  @Component({
    host: {
      '[class.active]': 'isActive',
      '(click)': 'onClick()',
      '[attr.role]': 'buttonRole'
    }
  })
  export class ButtonComponent {
    isActive = false;
    buttonRole = 'button';
    
    onClick() { /* ... */ }
  }
  
  // ❌ DON'T: Use separate decorators
  @Component({})
  export class ButtonComponent {
    @HostBinding('class.active')
    isActive = false;
    
    @HostBinding('attr.role')
    buttonRole = 'button';
    
    @HostListener('click')
    onClick() { /* ... */ }
  }
  ```